GQDs are known to exhibit the diagnostic Raman bands termed the G and D bands resulting from the E2g tangential vibrational mode of the sp2 bonded carbons and the disordered A1g breathing vibrational mode of the aromatic sp2 carbon rings, respectively. The uncoordinated GQDs displayed the characteristic Raman peaks at 1554 and 1385cm−1 for the G and D bands, respectively (Fig. 4
                           ). In contrast to the GQDs, the D and G bands of 5 (shown as an example in Fig. 4) or 6 shifted to higher wavenumbers by υ
                           =21 and 23cm−1, respectively. The observed shifts are attributed to the presence of π–π stacking interaction between the GQDs and the Pc complexes, resulting in a high density of sp2 bonds vibrations hence the shifts to higher wavenumber (cm−1) [40]. Defects of the graphene core structure of the GQDs are not expected since the π–π interaction preserves the structural integrity of both interacting molecules [7,41–43].

In order to further understand the extent of the mutual interactions between GQDs and the respective phthalocyanines and porphyrins, fluorescence quantum yields (ΦF(Pc/P)) and lifetimes (τ(Pc/P)) of complexes ZnTPyPc (1) and ZnTPyP (3) were evaluated (by exciting where Ps/Pcs absorb) in the presence of the GQDs. As shown in Table 1 (ΦF(Pc/P)
                            and τF(Pc/P)
                           ), there were slight increases in the fluorescence quantum yields (ΦF(Pc/P)
                           ) of the GQDs-ZnTPyPc (5) and GQDs-ZnTPyP (7) compared to ZnTPyPc (1) and ZnTPyP (3), this results are also reflected in the large increase in the fluorescence lifetimes (τF(Pc/P)
                           ) of the conjugates (Table 1). Co derivatives of the Pcs and Ps on the other hand, did not show any fluorescence emission, which are due to the paramagnetic nature of Co. Hence, results obtained were for the Zn derivatives only as shown in Table 1. The increases in the fluorescence parameters (ΦF(Pc/P)
                            and τF(Pc/P)
                           ) of the respective Pcs and Ps upon coordination to the GQDs could further be a demonstration that energy transfer process must have occurred between the GQDs and the respective Pcs and Ps, resulting in the quenching of the GQDs emission, since the GQDs acted as the energy donor to the Pcs and Ps.
